    <head>
        <title>Boxplot</title>
    </head>
    <body>
        <p>In this activity, we will use the Best Actor Oscar winners (1970-2013) to:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Learn how to use a statistics package to produce the numerical measures, or
                "descriptive statistics" of a distribution.</li>
            <li>Get some information about the distribution from its five-number summary.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Click <activity_link idref="bestactordataset_2013" target="new">here</activity_link> to
            see the entire dataset.</p>
        <pullout>
            <alternatives group="statistics.package">
                <default><pref:value preference="statistics.package"/></default>
                <alternative value="r">
                    <title>R Instructions</title>
                    <p>To open R with the dataset preloaded, right-click <link
                            href="../../../webcontent/r/actor_2013.RData" target="self">here</link>
                        and choose "Save Target As" to download the file to your computer. Then find
                        the downloaded file and double-click it to open it in R.</p>
                    <p>The data have been loaded into the data frame <code>actor_age</code>. Enter
                        the command <code>actor_age</code> to see the data. The only variable
                        (column title) in the data frame <code>actor_age</code> is
                        <code>Age</code>.</p>
                    <p>The following command will show you the five-number summary for the actors’
                        age data and the mean value of the data as well:</p>
                    <code style="inline">summary(actor_age$Age)</code>
                    <!--                    <codeblock syntax="text">     Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.
    31.00   37.75   42.50   44.72   48.75   76.00-->
                    <p>To get specific descriptive statistics from the data set consider the
                        following commands:</p>
                    <p>For the Mean:</p>
                    <code style="inline">mean(actor_age$Age)</code>
                    <!--<codeblock syntax="text">  [1] 44.71875</codeblock>-->
                    <p>For the Standard Deviation:</p>
                    <code style="inline">sd(actor_age$Age)</code>
                    <!--<codeblock syntax="text">  [1] 10.26499</codeblock>-->
                    <p>For the Variance:</p>
                    <code style="inline">var(actor_age$Age)</code>
                    <!--                    <codeblock syntax="text">  [1] 105.37</codeblock>-->
                    <p>For the Median:</p>
                    <code style="inline">median(actor_age$Age)</code>
                    <!--                    <codeblock syntax="text">  [1] 42.5</codeblock>-->
                    <p>For the Inter-quartile range:</p>
                    <code style="inline">IQR(actor_age$Age)</code>
                    <!--                    <codeblock syntax="text">  [1] 11</codeblock>-->
                    <p>For the Minimum:</p>
                    <code style="inline">min(actor_age$Age)</code>
                    <!--                    <codeblock syntax="text">  [1] 31</codeblock>-->
                    <p>For the Maximum:</p>
                    <code style="inline">max(actor_age$Age)</code>
                    <!--                    <codeblock syntax="text">  [1] 76</codeblock>-->
                    <p>For the Sample Size (n):</p>
                    <code style="inline">length(actor_age$Age)</code>
                    <!--                    <codeblock syntax="text">  [1] 32</codeblock>-->
                    <p>For the First Quartile (25th percentile, Q1):</p>
                    <code style="inline">quantile(actor_age$Age, 0.25)</code>
                    <!--                    <codeblock syntax="text">    25%
  37.75</codeblock>-->
                    <p>For the Third Quartile (75th percentile, Q3):</p>
                    <code style="inline">quantile(actor_age$Age, 0.75)</code>
                    <!--                    <codeblock syntax="text">    75%
  48.75-->

                </alternative>
                <alternative value="StatCrunch">
                    <title>StatCrunch Instructions</title>
                    <p>To open the file (actor.xls) in StatCrunch, you must first right-click <link
                            href="../../../webcontent/excel/actor_2013.xls" target="self"
                            >here</link> and choose "Save Target As" to download the file to your
                        computer. Next click <link href="http://www.statcrunch.com/" target="new"
                            >here</link> to open StatCrunch in a separate window and login using
                        your username and password.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Click on the link “Open StatCrunch” at the top of the My StatCrunch
                            page. </li>
                        <li>To open the data set, click on the Data button in the top row and select
                            Load → From file → on my computer.</li>
                        <li>Under File, press the Browse button and select the data set you
                            downloaded.</li>
                        <li>Scroll to the bottom of the page and click on “Load File.”</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>To ask StatCrunch for the descriptive statistics of a distribution:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Choose Stat → Summary Stats → Columns</li>
                        <li>In the Column Statistics window select the column Age</li>
                        <li>Press Compute! </li>
                    </ul>
                </alternative>
                <alternative value="minitab">
                    <title>Minitab Instructions</title>
                    <p>To open the actor's age dataset, right-click <link
                            href="../../../webcontent/minitab/actor_2013.mtw" target="self"
                            >here</link> and choose "Save Target As" to download the file to your
                        computer. Then find the downloaded file and double-click it to open it in
                        Minitab. Note: you will likely see a dialog box appear that says "A copy of
                        the content of this file will be added to the current project"&#8212;just
                        click "OK."</p>
                    <p>To ask Minitab for the descriptive statistics of a distribution: </p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Choose: Stat → Basic Statistics → Display Descriptive Statistics</li>
                        <li>Under "Variables" type age (or double click on this variable in the left
                            panel)</li>
                        <li>Click OK</li>
                    </ul>
                </alternative>
                <alternative value="excel">
                    <title>Excel 2013 and 2016 Instructions</title>
                    <p>To open the dataset, click <link
                            href="../../../webcontent/excel/actor_2013.xls" target="self"
                            >here</link> to download the file to your computer. Then find the
                        downloaded file and double-click it to open it in Excel. When Excel opens
                        you may have to enable editing.</p>
                    <p>Now use Excel to calculate the numerical measures of a distribution: </p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><em>min</em></li>
                        <li>Pick a cell outside of column A, and type <em>min</em>.</li>
                        <li>Then, in the next cell to the right, type <em>=min(A2:A33)</em>.</li>
                        <li><em>IMPORTANT:</em> Instead of typing the <em>A2:A33</em> inside of the
                            parentheses, it is better to highlight the relevant cells with your
                            mouse after typing <em>=min(</em> (by holding a left click as you highlight the
                            cells).</li>
                    </ul>
                    <ul>

                        <li><em>Q1</em></li>
                        <li>In the cell under <em>min</em>, type <em>Q1</em>.</li>
                        <li>Then, in the next cell to the right, type
                            <em>=quartile(A2:A33,1)</em>.</li>
                        <li>Note: <em>=quartile.inc(A2:A33, 1)</em> will also work.</li>
                    </ul>

                    <ul>
                        <li><em>Median</em></li>
                        <li>In the cell under <em>Q1</em>, type <em>Median</em>.</li>
                        <li>Then, in the next cell to the right, type <em>=median(A2:A33)</em>.</li>
                        <li>Note: <em>=quartile(A2:A33, 2)</em> will also work.</li>
                    </ul>

                    <ul>
                        <li><em>Mean</em></li>
                        <li>In the cell under <em>Median</em>, type <em>Mean</em>.</li>
                        <li>Then, in the next cell to the right, type
                            <em>=average(A2:A33)</em>.</li>
                    </ul>

                    <ul>
                        <li><em>Q3</em></li>
                        <li>In the cell under <em>Mean</em>, type <em>Q3</em>.</li>
                        <li>Then, in the next cell to the right, type
                            <em>=quartile(A2:A33,3)</em>.</li>
                    </ul>

                    <ul>
                        <li><em>Max</em></li>
                        <li>In the cell under <em>Q3</em>, type <em>Max</em>.</li>
                        <li>Then, in the next cell to the right, type <em>=max(A2:A33)</em>.</li>
                    </ul>
